				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: EQ2 bard<a name="67641"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Oct 20 04 10:10 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>A Developer's Explanation of Heroic Opportunities.  As usual, anything that overcomplicates things, I am compelled to become an expert at, so ask any questions you might have, hehe...
<br />

<br />
<blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">Opportunity breakdown
<br />

<br />
Hey everyone,
<br />

<br />
A detailed explanation of heroic opportunities below:
<br />

<br />
Opportunity Icons
<br />

<br />
Opportunity icons are the building blocks of heroic opportunities. Each spell or combat art used by players has an opportunity icon associated with it, which can trigger or advance a heroic opportunity. The icons are divided into four groups, one for each archetype.
<br />

<br />
Fighter (blue)
<br />
Sword
<br />
Shield
<br />
Horn
<br />
Fist
<br />
Boot
<br />
Flexed arm
<br />

<br />
Priest (gold)
<br />
Chalice
<br />
Holy Symbol
<br />
Hammer
<br />
Eye
<br />
Moon
<br />
Druidic Stones
<br />

<br />
Scout (green)
<br />
Dagger
<br />
Bow
<br />
Mask
<br />
Lock
<br />
Cloak
<br />
Coin
<br />

<br />
Mage (red)
<br />
Wand
<br />
Lightning
<br />
Tome
<br />
Staff
<br />
Fire
<br />
Star
<br />

<br />
Starter chains are a sequence of icons that can trigger a heroic opportunity. When completed, heroic opportunities cast a spell effect that benefits the party.
<br />

<br />
1.) Open a starter chain
<br />
A starter chain appears when you use a spell or combat art that happens to be the first link in a starter chain. When the chain is initiated, the icon of the spell or combart art that began it appears in the center of a circle with possible link icons around it that are blinking.
<br />

<br />
2.) Continue the chain
<br />
Use a spell or combat art that has one of the link icons associated with it. This responsibility is shared by the entire party. If anyone in the group uses a spell or combat art other than one with a matching icon, then the starter chain is lost and a new one must be started from scratch.
<br />

<br />
3.) Completing a Starter Chain
<br />
Repeat step two until a starter chain is complete. If completed, the starter chain initiates a heroic opportunity from its opportunity list. Currently each starter chain can choose one of three opportunities: common, uncommon, or rare.
<br />

<br />
4a.) Heroic Opportunity Completion
<br />
The party can complete a heroic opportunity by using spells and abilities with icons that match those in he opportunity wheel. Sometimes an opportunity wheel requires the opportunities to be completed in a certain order; other times it does not. If one of your abilities can advance the opportunity wheel, the icon for that spell or combat art will blink.
<br />

<br />
Using a spell or combat art that doesn't match the next icon in the wheel does not cancel the opportunity; however, it will not advance the opportunity wheel. Each opportunity has a time limit of 30 seconds; if it isn't completed in that time, the opportunity fails.
<br />

<br />
4b.) Heroic Opportunity Shift
<br />
Each opportunity has a special shift icon associated with it: the coin. Scouts may use combat arts with that symbol to shift to another heroic opportunity. They may do this only once and must use the ability before any others have been used to advance the opportunity wheel.
<br />

<br />
NOTE: Currently, shifting will allow 
<br />

<br />
Starter Chains
<br />

<br />
Currently 15 different starter chains exist, one for each combination of archetype professions. The single profession starter chains are as follows:
<br />

<br />
Fighter: boot – sword – taunt
<br />
Scout: cloak – dagger
<br />
Priest: druidic stone – hammer
<br />
Mage: star - lightning 
<br />

<br />
Feel free to ask questions if you are confused by my explanation. Also, I realize some of these may be out of whack balance wise. If you see any that you believe are either too weak or too powerful  please, let me know.
<br />

<br />
-Tom
<br />

<br />
Forgot this part:
<br />

<br />
Heroic Opportunity effects use the level of the encounter engaged to determine their power. So, if used to fight greys the effects will be much lower than against NPCs equal level or higher.
<br />

<br />

<br />
Edit: Fixed formatting. Added explanation on encounters determining relative power of an opportunity.
<br />

<br />
