			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: EQ2 bard<a name="67813"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Oct 22 04 12:51 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span><blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">Lol, that looks like something that might become clearer with use. 
<br />

<br />
Are the icons for the starter chains only used to start the starter chains, or are they spells/actions that have some value in and of themselves? 
<br />
</span></blockquote>
<br />
Spells, Songs, and Combat Arts have an additions &quot;Rune&quot; when you examine them (right click and view the description).  They generally make sense with some form of catagory of stuff for that class.  The Priest (yellow) runes for example:  chalice = various insta-heals, druid stones = various regens, moon = various wards (runes-- dmg absorbtion), hammer = nukes.
<br />
<blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">
<br />
If so, do they 'make sense' when you do them in the required order, or does it cause you to perform less than beneficial acts to get/keep the chain going. 
<br />
</span></blockquote>
<br />

<br />
It's a bit of a mix.  Most of the Starter Chains do make sense though, especially on a pull.  One of my favorites, for example:
<br />

<br />
Scout Ambush (Cloak Starter Rune-- stealthy WHAM! attack)
<br />
Fighter Shout (Horn Rune-- AE Taunt)
<br />
Priest Ward (Moon Rune -- dmg absorbtion)
<br />
Mage Nuke (Flame Rune)
<br />

<br />
Starter Chain complete, HO Wheel is up.
<br />
<blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">
<br />
Ditto on the heroic acts? 
<br />
</span></blockquote>
<br />
Now, these make a little less &quot;sense&quot; from a tactical point of view.  In fact, some of the better (harder) ones have wierd stuff in them that you normally might NOT do in combat.  You have 30 seconds, however, to figure it out and do it.  AND, once the Wheel itself is up, anyone can do anything, and it doesn't stop the HO.  (Unlike Starter Chains, where you must be careful not to break it).
<br />

<br />
Now, though the moves in an HO sometimes don't make &quot;sense&quot;, they give interesting names to the effects that DO make sense to what runes or classes are doing the HO.  For example, there are a bunch of HOs that have Scout Cloak runes in them, and they have names with &quot;Luck&quot; or &quot;Trickery&quot; in them.  &quot;Luck's Bite&quot; is a DD that has Fighter Boot (Kick) and Scout Cloak.  &quot;Arcane Trickery&quot; has a mage something and Scout Cloak.  &quot;Piercing Faith&quot; has Fighter Sword and Priest Hammer runes.
<br />
<blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">
<br />
If two of the same class do the same action at nearly the same time, does it blow the starter? I'm guessing this requires some, or maybe a significant amount of group coordination? 
<br />
</span></blockquote>
<br />
Yes, Starter Chains get messed up easily.  Yes, groups must work together and cooperate.  This is what I like most about it, (and what is most challenging, hehe).  Often they are easier to pull off in smaller groups than full ones for that reason.  Which is pretty cool, because it kind of balances things out, giving extra help to a group that isn't full or completely balanced.
<br />
<blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">
<br />
I'll bop over to the EQII site and see if I can figure some stuff out for myself. 
<br />

<br />
Like I said, looks like using it might clear some things up. </span></blockquote>
<br />

<br />
It takes people a while ingame to get the hang of them.  So, no big suprise that just READING about it would be hard to picture, hehe.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
